==English==
===Etymology===
From Middle English ''scateren'' < Old English ''sceaterian'', probably from a dialect of Old Norse. Cf. Low German ''schateren'' and Dutch ''[[schateren]]'' ('to burst out laughing').

===Transitive verb===
'''to scatter''' ([[scatters]], [[scattered]], [[scattering]])

#To cause to [[separate]] and go in different directions.
#To [[distribute]] [[loosely]] as by [[sprinkle|sprinkling]].
#{{Physics}} To [[deflect]] (radiation or particles).

